text_answer.content: The reading level for the passages is great for 8th grade, and the first passage is totally fine for the tutoring context, but I'm concerned about the second passage. A student spending her summer vacation with her dad in the hospital would be managing so much personally and emotionally...I don't think she would be thinking about a science fair project for the following school year. The topic itself could possibly be triggering for any student who lost someone during COVID or has experienced parents or loved ones on a ventilator in the hospital. Even if Thalia's friend and teacher (who is available on summer break?) helped her create a makeshift ventilation system, that system would not be used to help her father or anyone else that summer. Overall, the second passage is poorly written and does not seem appropriate for the tutoring context.

text_answer.content: I'm not sure why neither passage uses Sacagawea's name, but that is the person they are both referring to. I'm not sure why the second passage uses an entirely different name while recounting Sacagawea's story. I think Sacagawea's name should be used in both passages. Also, I noticed that the first passage said the expedition started in 1804 and "after an arduous journey of nearly two and a half years..." they reached the Pacific Ocean in November 1805. The math doesn't add up. The expedition in total could have taken two and a half years, but it didn't take the party two and a half years to reach the Pacific. Also, I don't think there is enough evidence to support the inference suggested in the fifth reading comprehension question.
